>I'm motivated to ask this question by the following sort of situation. =20
>Johnson and Morton claim that there are two systems connected with the=20
>recognition of face vs. non-face stimuli.  The first, conspec, is=20
>present at birth and supports orienting to face-like stimuli.  The=20
>second, conlearn, develops in the first 2 months or so and supports the=20
>smooth tracking of faces and is more sophisticated in how it recognises=20
>faces.  Since the development of conlearn depends on experience there's=20
>a fairly clear sense in which it is not innate.  However, I suppose it=20
>might be plausible think of 'innate' as contrasting with 'learnt'.  And=20
>although I suppose there is some sense in which the development of=20
>conlearn involves learning from experience, equally it seems to me that=20
>when theorising about capacities that involve more reflective learning=20
>such as, say, abilities to categorise familiar people by kinship=20
>relation, it is natural to take face recognition to be an innate=20
>capacity--or, rather, as a more innate capacity--partly because face=20
>recognition involves unreflective learning and partly because it seems=20
>to provide a foundation for the subsequent learning about things like=20
>kinship.=20
